              "narration_script": "Challenge debrief. Your response has been submitted. Infection prevention starts with the action that breaks the chain of transmission for every resident, not just the ones who look sick. Hand hygiene, done correctly and at the right moments, is that action. The safest response is to hand hygiene performed correctly and at the right times. Hand hygiene performed correctly and at the right times is the single most effective way to prevent the spread of infection in long-term care. Hands are the main way germs travel between residents, surfaces, and you, so clean hands before and after every contact stop transmission at its most common point. As a CNA, stay within scope: observe, report, document, and follow the care plan. Resident safety and dignity come first, so report any change of condition promptly to the nurse. Before you continue, review the safest response and your own choice so the reason stays with you on the floor.",
