              "display_title": "Complications of Inactivity",
              "learner_facing_content": "CCCCO Module 14 lists many complications of inactivity: stress, depression, behavior and sleep changes, stasis pneumonia or atelectasis, thrombophlebitis, pulmonary embolism, contractures, osteoporosis, muscle atrophy, pressure sores, constipation, decreased appetite, urinary complications, loneliness, and depression.\n\nA CNA does not diagnose these complications, but CNAs often notice early warning signs: less participation, shortness of breath, cough, pain, swelling, skin change, constipation, poor appetite, toileting changes, or new sadness and withdrawal. Report changes promptly so the nurse and care team can respond.",
