              "display_title": "Reporting a Near-Fall",
              "learner_facing_content": "A near-fall is evidence. If the resident stumbles, grabs furniture, knees buckle, becomes dizzy, has a sudden gait change, or needs more help than usual, treat it as a change worth reporting. CCCCO Module 14 directs CNAs to report significant changes, and CCCCO Module 12 emphasizes recognizing distress and responding.\n\nDocument what happened objectively: where the resident was, what assistance was being given, what device was used, what the resident said, and what you observed. Do not simply write \"almost fell\" without details. Report promptly so the nurse can reassess risk and update the plan.",
