              "display_title": "Dysphagia and Choking Risk",
              "learner_facing_content": "Residents at high risk for dysphagia and choking include those with stroke, neurological disease, head/neck/throat trauma, or dementia. CCCCO Module 11 lists warning signs to report: long intervals before swallowing, swallowing several times with each bite, frequent throat clearing, difficulty handling food or fluids in the mouth, wet or gurgling voice, pocketing food, excessive drooling, or the feeling that food is sticking.\n\nPrevention starts with following the individual feeding plan: small bites, small amounts, enough time to chew and swallow, close supervision, ordered thickened liquids, and upright positioning during and after meals.",
