              "display_title": "IV Fluids and Nutrition: What the CNA Reports",
              "learner_facing_content": "The CCCCO source also describes intravenous infusion as ordered by the physician and started and monitored by a licensed nurse according to facility policy. CNA responsibilities are observation and reporting, not adjustment.\n\nKeep IV tubing free from kinks, twisting, pressure, or obstruction. Report alarms, pain or burning at the IV site, swelling or redness, fever, difficulty breathing, bleeding or leakage, disconnected tubing, or an empty IV fluid container. The CNA should never adjust or turn off IV monitoring equipment and should make sure the resident or family does not handle, adjust, or stop the infusion. Escalate concerns promptly to the licensed nurse.",
