              "display_title": "Pressure Injuries: Recognize Risk, Do Not Diagnose",
              "learner_facing_content": "CCCCO Module 13 defines pressure sores as a break in skin integrity that develops over a bony prominence as a result of pressure. The source describes staged changes, but a CNA does not independently diagnose, stage, or treat a pressure injury.\n\nThe CNA learns the warning signs to report: redness over a bony prominence that does not go away, blue or black color changes on darker skin, abrasions, blisters, shallow crater, deeper crater, exposed deeper tissue, pain, warmth, drainage, or any open area. Use plain objective descriptions. For example: \"left heel red and warm after repositioning\" is safer than writing a stage unless the nurse has documented it.",
