              "display_title": "Rules of Legal Documentation",
              "learner_facing_content": "Your documentation is a legal record. It can be used in court, reviewed by surveyors, and referenced by the entire care team. Follow these rules:\nDocument promptly. Record observations as soon as possible after the event.\nBe objective. Write what happened, not what you think happened. Use measurable terms.\nBe specific. Instead of \"ate well,\" write \"consumed 75% of lunch.\"\nUse the resident's words in quotes. \"Resident stated: 'My back hurts when I move.'\"\nUse approved abbreviations only. If you are unsure about an abbreviation, write the full word.\nNever erase, use white-out, or scribble over entries. For paper records, draw a single line through the error, write \"error,\" initial, and date.\nSign every entry with your name, title (CNA), date, and time.\nNever chart in advance. Only document what has already happened.\nNever chart for someone else. Each CNA documents their own observations.\nIf you didn't document it, it didn't happen. This is a legal principle.",
              "learning_goal": "Differentiate between objective and subjective observations.",
              "cna_practice_example": "Connect this screen to a routine CNA decision, then report concerns to the licensed nurse as appropriate.",
              "why_it_matters": [
                "Supports safe CNA judgment within scope of practice.",
                "Builds audit-ready completion evidence for required online theory only.",
                "Preserves compliance boundaries: no PHI, no clinical-hour credit, certificate production disabled."
              ],
              "key_terms": [],
